caption_original:
How can oats be more efficient?  In 2008, the AC Gehl, a hulless, hairless oat variety was released after 15 years of work by Agriculture and Agri-Food Canada scientist Vern Burrows.  The new oat is easier and more efficient to harvest and process, and because the hull is already gone, it's also cheaper to transport! 
Celebrate 150 years of agriculture and learn more intriguing facts: ow.ly/gdif30dy4G2

caption_original:
Isn’t this amazing?!? Back in the spring, AAFC scientists and the @AgMuseum participated in the @SoilCanada #SoilYourUndies campaign and buried some cotton underwear to test the soil’s microbiology; Healthy soil has lots of organisms that breakdown organic matter and fibres. We hoped to see some visible breakdown after our undies had been buried for several weeks.
The results we dug up were pretty conclusive – there was nothing left but the elastics!
If you want to test your own soil microbiology, instructions for the #SoilYourUndies campaign are available from the @SoilCouncil website:

On July 1, 1867, the federal Department of Agriculture was created and Jean-Charles Chapais, the first Minister of Agriculture, was appointed. Back then, in addition to agriculture, the minister’s responsibilities included arts and manufactures, immigration, quarantine, public health and the census and statistics, among others. 

Celebrate #HistoryWeek2017 and visit: ow.ly/hyDe30dm6jC
